segments.text: And he ended up as a full general command of the Air Force Command, and he retired not too long ago.
Yeah, right.
Oh, yeah, I remember he was the first black officer in the Air Force.
I mean the highest, the first one to become general, I mean.
Yeah, yeah.
And he was under your command?
At Massawa, yeah.
He must have been good then.
Yeah, he was real, I mean he was real good.
Mm-hmm.
And my wife was mentioning last night that actually we had one colored pilot that came into Massawa down to Isozuki when we were there.
And no one wanted to fly with him.
Really?
And so I said, okay, I'll be his co-pilot.
So I took on the job of being his co-pilot.
Then it just, everything fell in the line.
So he wasn't...
He wasn't put on a pedestal or he had any problems, which I'd forgotten about, but he was probably my first, and I don't remember his name.
Well that was, you were demonstrating to them that if you could do it, they could do it.
Yeah, they could do it.
If I didn't mind by then, then they shouldn't mind type of thing.
Well that was a good idea.
Now, it seems like what you're doing when you become the commander of the 39th Air Division is you're immediately trying to demonstrate that you're different from the former commander.
Well, I think that's a... Is that the theme?
That's the theme.
Because he had been a poor commander and you wanted to get this place in shape.
Now, was that a threat that your commander told you that he's giving you three months?
Did you take it as a threat?
Oh, yeah, well, no.

Well, actually, I took it a different way in that I took it with the idea that he'd just give me a free rein of doing whatever I thought was necessary to getting Masawa kind of straightened out, and that he wasn't going to be sending any IG teams up there to investigate some of my programs or anything like this.
And of course I kept him informed.
Sure.
What he think of sending 250 men back to the states?
Well, he didn't object.
I mean as far as I was concerned, I figured I could get along without those 250 without even any replacements.
I think some of the men and people when they got back to the port of embarkation here in the States were taken off of the discharge list and reassigned.
But he supported me a hundred percent.
Another thing you said about that is that
I could do it then, but I probably couldn't get away with that today in the Air Force.
What could you explain?
Well, today why you have the minority is the underdog type of thing, that you just can't discharge a lot of people.
for offenses such as being drunk and disorderly, this type of thing.
And it's a lot harder to bypass what you might call civil rights.
I mean, this is a civil right.
I mean, an individual, some guy is just deciding that because he has been drunk and disorderly two or three times that he was
unsatisfactory to the Air Force and he was sending him home just upon his own judgment.
The individual's civil rights were being violated.
So you had to go into a big board and have a group of individuals decide whether or not I was right or wrong.
But did you think back in 1959 that you were violating their civil rights?
And do you think that today?
No, I don't think.
I just think that it was just a matter of circumstances.
And I would certainly say that a percentage of those, maybe 25%, or 33% or 30%, could have been rehabilitated.
As far as I'm concerned at the time, I just didn't have time.
What happened to this man, this Lieutenant Colonel?
He was a fairly high ranking officer, and he was the highest one that you sent back.
What happened to him?
He was one of the ones that was pulled off at the POE and reassigned.
I mean, as far as I was concerned, it was always alright with me.
I didn't make any difference.
You just wanted to get rid of them from your base.
I wanted to get them out of my base.
Now, you were talking about being drunk and disorderly.
What other type of offenses would you send these officers and enlisted men home for?
Just any time they went up twice to Captain's Mass or?

No, well, see you had an article, what you call an article 15, where the individual appeared before the commander, his commander, for being absent from AWOL for a couple days, or numerous speeding violations on base, or
which indicated that he really didn't pay too much attention to regulation.
And in those cases, he had to have done this two or three times, I mean four, five, six times.
It wasn't just a one or two or three time offense.
So I was looking for individuals who really didn't pay too much attention to
regulations and that they're maintaining airplanes, why they would have the same attitude.
You also mentioned, one of the things that you mentioned was some gentleman, and this I think is interesting, some gentleman, something about his morals.
He was married and he was running around with Japanese women or something like that.
Well, he was living, he was sleeping off base with some Japanese woman.
He had a wife and a bunch of kids at home.
Back in the United States.
Back in the United States.
And was it pretty typical to discipline back in 1959 in the 50s Air Force?
Was it fairly typical for a general officer, his commanding officer then, to discipline this man?
Was he an enlisted man or an officer?
No, he was an officer.
He was an officer.
And I consider that as conduct unbecoming of an officer and a gentleman.
And it was just one of my standards.
Maybe somebody else wouldn't have...
Wouldn't have done that.
But it straightens up the base real fast.
I mean, maybe I just select one, and he goes on.
But all the rest of them are doing the same thing.
They move back on base real fast.
OK. Now, what other responsibilities did you have besides getting this base into shape as the commander of the 39th Air Division?
Well, there are numerous things that you do, whether it was not too long after the war or after the Korean War.
And you, as the air bases closed up, the Air Force air bases closed up, all of the spare equipment on base, on those bases, like
was moved down to Misawa.
So you end up on base with numerous warehouses full of all kinds of equipment.
I think we had, going around and searching all the buildings, we found around a dozen rotating beacons that you put up on a tower at each base so that the pilot can see it and head.
Well, we had about eight there.
that had been shipped in or offloaded from some boat probably during, after the war or after World War II or during the Korean War.
And so we established a program of
of shipping out, declaring a surplus, all of these spare equipment.
And we shipped out millions of dollars, declared a surplus, and shipped them back to the States, or shipped them to other bases where you had a need for them.
And so you get your supply down.
Instead of being in four warehouses, you get your supply down into two warehouses.
And you go through your stock records and the same thing.
You have the items that you currently use.
Like in an automotive parts warehouse, you'd have six generators for one particular Chevrolet sedan.
and you look at the record and maybe you used one of those per year and you had six of them.
Well, you declare a surplus of six of them to be shipped to some other base or to be disposed of.
So you got into a stock record type of management program where you just saved the Air Force a lot of money.
And you have some time you have to warehouse that for six years while it would probably become rusted anyway.
So we had a big program established to cut down and as commander I think that there's nothing more important than having someone hear the footsteps of the boss.
And you go around and check your stock records and he knows you're going to come around and
and check his stock records, and so he will do it himself.
When I left there, I was given a metal machine, the sheet metal shopper made up a box, which is bits and pieces.
I was always going around and opening drawers
and checking on all these spare parts that they had.
So they made up this kit and they had everything in the world.
This was presented to me when I left there.
Presented to me and they had everything in there.
They had a dead frog that somebody had opened a drawer and there was a dead frog in it.
So they dried, you know,
So they put that in there.
So all kinds of miscellaneous bits and pieces that I was known for.
And the other thing you can do is, and this is kind of, I'll agree this is some of these kind of nasty, you know.
I'd go down to BX during duty hours and I'd stop maybe three or four airmen and find out where they worked.
And then I'd run out of the BX and down to the flight line and I'd go to the line chief and I'd say, Robin, I'd like to look at some of your airplanes here and see what you're doing.
And so these boys, there were a couple of boys who were down at the BX, I said, well, where is John Doe?
He said, oh, he's around here someplace.
And I said, well, why don't we find him?
I know he's down there, he's down at the BX in the base exchange or down there getting coffee or something.
And so we'd try to find him.
And then we couldn't find him.
And I said, well, it looks like to me that you just don't need him.
So I just cut one guy off over this guy's management.
Well, he was maybe a
may have been assistant crew chief or helper or something of this sort.
I said, well, I'll just cut one man off your authorization for manpower.
And he told me that he had given him permission to go to BX to get a cup of coffee.
That's all I wanted.
I mean, as long as he knew where the guy was.
But if he didn't know where he was, then I knew he wasn't supervising very well.
So you were keeping them on their toes.
Oh, yeah.
Well, that's the type of individual I was.
I delved into all the little activities of everybody.
And I think, as I said, I think there's nothing more important than hearing the footsteps of the boss.
And then I would be out on the flight line watching the safety procedures and refueling airplanes.
Prior to that they had some airplanes burn up when they were refueling.
Well the airplane wouldn't be properly grounded or the fuel nozzle wasn't properly grounded when it came in contact with the airplane and that causes spark and that's how it burned up.
So you have to
Then you'd get everybody's brother out there showing them what they were doing differently.
So you had to be smart enough to know what the procedures were to start with.
That's the type of commander I was.
I was a detailed type of commander.
I got into everybody's business and I didn't sit around the office very much.
writing instructions to somebody.
I was out there and I got the best people in the top jobs.
I mean the best majors were the squadron commanders and the best sergeants were the crew chiefs and they didn't like it because it's cold on the outside.
as long as they got behind the program.
And then when you get something started, like this is the best air force, best radio school, the same thing there.
This is the best fighter out there.
And everybody gets behind it.
In fact, you get to the point where in some cases the pilots took unnecessary risk in landing an airplane with a dead engine on the runway.
So you give him heck for taking too much of a chance, because you're really interested in saving his life, and it would have been better for him to jump out.
But we had a guy, and of course you laud him for doing it, but you think he's crazy for doing it to start with.
But he landed an F-102.
without engines on the runway.
He just glided in?
Well, he just glided in.
And he did a marvelous job.
And so you didn't have an accident.
So you went nine months without an accident.
And you had to be kind of a showman type ship, I think, to be a real good commander.
Like before I went up to Missoula,
General Burns had a flying safety conference of all the wing commanders and their flying safety officers and what have you.
So, at 379th I had a very good flying safety program there.
So, I had gone around to all the bases, the wings before I went up there.
and looked at everybody's flying safety program and inspected their bases.
So I knew what everybody was doing good and what everybody was doing bad.
And you just plagiarize.
You plagiarize all good ideas.
And so when I went up there, I had a list of all the best pilots and the ones that had two or three accidents.
So you knew the ones to watch on.
you knew what everybody else was doing, so it is safety.
I had not just been up to Pasado maybe a week.
I went down and told them, I said, I'm going to go six months without an aircraft accident.
And I told them, this is what I'm going to do.
And one of them was that the top maintenance officer in the squadron was going to be the flying safety officer.
So not only was he
Main, he was also a pilot.
No, they were all pilots.
Not only that, was he a good pilot, but he was also a good maintenance officer.
We had on base a RECO squadron which belonged to the wing of Tachikawa.
I wrote a note to the squadron commander, told him to provide me with the best pilot and the best maintenance officer.

Well, he furnished me with the name of an inexperienced pilot, although he may have been, he was young, so I called him up and I said, look, you provide the guy that was not qualified, so here's the guy I want.
So I just picked out his best guy and said, yeah, he's a flying safety officer for this squadron.
Well, the wing commander got upset with me, but as I announced at this
down there.
I said, well, this is what I did.

Of course, John Burns backed me up and after the other wing commander of this reconnaissance outfit we became very good friends because his squadron up there did the same things everybody else was doing.
So you get up there with a flare and say, you're going to do this.
Well, I mean, you're taking a big chance.
I'll agree you're taking a big chance.
So you had put pressures on you to be sure that you could produce.
What did General Burns think?
It sounds like you had quite a few accomplishments up there.
What did General Burns think of this?
Well, see, I was, that's when I was selected from up there and went into the PACAF headquarters.
recommended for promotion to Major General there and I don't know.
You were as, when you were in Missoula, you were recommended?
No, well he selected me for, see that was a Brigadier General slot, so he selected me to come to headquarters PACAF and to be the, his deputy for plans and operations.
as a result of what I did up there.
I see, so he was quite happy with your job.
Oh yeah, he was.
And he tried to promote you to a two-star general.
Oh yeah, he would come up on visits and listen to General O'Donnell.
He said, I had everybody so scared up there that they were just afraid to have an accident.
So, I mean, kidding, you know.
But, no, I thoroughly enjoyed it up there.
It was up in the boondocks of Massawa.
We, in the wintertime, no one ever bothered you because you were just almost no then, and so you just were able to run your base just about the way you wanted to, your division.
and I think everybody pretty well liked it.
Sounds like a real challenge too.
Oh yeah.
So I stayed two years up there and that was probably my, I enjoyed that probably as good as anything because I knew what I was doing.
At that stage you get to the point where you know exactly what you're doing.
See back in the 315th division
way back at Itazuki where that was really your first command and the rest of them you were training, you were in training.
That was the first flying command that you had, so you really didn't know what you were doing.
Then I moved from there into PACAF headquarters.
Before we get to Hawaii, let's talk about waste and military.
Often, every time a fiscal budget comes up, people are talking about waste and military.
It sounds like you're trying to prevent that.
It sounds like one of your major jobs is the 39th Air Division, as the commander there was, to cut waste.
Is that the way military commanders operate?
Well, I think that you have a number of problems.
One of them is
Occasionally you come down from the Secretary of Defense an automatic cut.
You have to cut 5% of your personnel.
Well, you have to keep about a 5% cushion because if you really did your best job and say, okay, I can cut this guy and this guy and this guy out of the staff and I can get along
with 200 less people, and this gets down to the bare bones situation, then somebody higher up will say automatically you just cut 5%.
Well, then you have a problem, because then you're below what requires to get your job done.
So you do have to keep a little slack in.
But otherwise, as far as management of materiel,
why I think that the Air Force has some of the best managers that you can find.
I mean, you hear that they sent me to all kinds of schools.
I mean, they train you in management.
I'd go on to Orlando, take a high-level management course.
George Washington University, why they had...
management course of four or five weeks that you attend.
They give you plenty of opportunity to become a good manager.
As far as I'm concerned, the managers in the Air Force are
It's about as good as you can find anywhere in the world.
I think the only problem you have is they're underpaid.
You just think of a squaring commander that has 25 airplanes and whatever it is, 300 or 400 people that he's running, and you're paying him a paltry salary of maybe $18,000 a year or $17,000 a year.
And you get out in civilian life, and you look at some salesman who works for a wholesale grocery company, an institutional grocer, and he's making $60,000 a year as both a basic salary plus a bonus.
And he's home Friday afternoon at around 2 o'clock.
He has no responsibilities until Monday morning.
He goes out and makes his calls again.
And it's to me why the cream of the Air Force, a guy if he's real smart, he won't stay in the Air Force.
There are so many jobs in civilian life that if you, and I'm on a soapbox now, that the commanders, these guys are willing to get out in front and make decisions.
they are the ones that we should be paying.
Yeah.
Now that we're on this topic, we have a similar situation in the profession of teaching.
That's right.
In which

people who have gone to school and done a lot of research and written many different articles and books, publications, are making maybe $20,000, $30,000 a year, where if they had that type of a position, or they might be a department head like at Texas A&M, but if they had that type of position where they'd be in charge of 40 or 50 people, they'd be making three or four times that much in the business world.
But the question is,
Is there a sense of duty in both of these types of jobs?
In the Air Force, for example, isn't pay secondary to the challenge and to the duty, or am I being too idealistic?
Can I get a cup of coffee?
No, you just go ahead.
Would you like one?
Well, why don't we cut it off, and I'll get a cup of tea.
